div></div></a></figure></div><p>For all its flaws, though, America is still=
 the best country in the world. And I say that as someone who has spent mos=
t of my adult life living abroad. Ever since I left home in California at t=
he age of 17, I=E2=80=99ve spent nearly a decade overseas. </p><p>3.5 years=
 stationed in Ramstein Air Base, Germany. 6 months deployed in Manas Air Ba=
se, Kyrgyzstan and Al Udeid Air Base, Qatar. 6 years living in the UK, with=
 4 years dedicated to completing my PhD at the University of Cambridge and =
an additional 2 years staying on a visa. With plenty of travel to many othe=
r countries during this period. </p><p>So I=E2=80=99m glad to be returning =
to the land of the free. Or at least the land where you can=E2=80=99t get a=
rrested for social media posts.</p><p><span>Not sure how long I=E2=80=99ll =
reside in NY. Perhaps a year. Perhaps two. Eventually, I=E2=80=99ll probabl=
y settle, for better or worse, back in California (maybe San Diego or there=
abouts). The very first time I visited New York in 2014 (hard to believe it=
=E2=80=99s been a full decade now), I was still on active duty in the milit=
ary. I stopped by the 9/11 memorial. It was under construction and heavily =
guarded by NYPD officers in order to prevent entry. I wanted to see it. My =
friend who was with me (a Yale graduate who tutored me at the Warrior-Schol=
ar Project, which I describe in </span><a href=3D"https://www.amazon.com/Tr=
oubled-Memoir-Foster-Family-Social/dp/1982168536/ref=3Dtmm_hrd_swatch_0?_en=
coding=3DUTF8&amp;qid=3D1687225601&amp;sr=3D8-2-fkmr2" rel=3D"">my book</a>=
<span>) said, =E2=80=9CRob, I=E2=80=99ll bet if you show them your military=
 ID they=E2=80=99ll let you through.=E2=80=9D I was skeptical but then appr=
oached one of the cops. The NYPD officer carefully examined my U.S. Air For=
ce ID, spoke a few words into his radio to notify his supervisor, and permi=
tted my entry, allowing me to tour the memorial alone for about 15 minutes.=
 </span></p><p>This isn=E2=80=99t just a geographic shift. It's a personal =
one, too. New York represents a new chapter. Full of uncertainty, possibili=
ty, and=E2=80=94if I=E2=80=99m being honest=E2=80=94a little bit of chaos. =
There=E2=80=99s something magnetic about the energy of the city. Yes, it=E2=
=80=99s dirty and has plenty of issues. It=E2=80=99s also a place where cre=
ativity thrives amidst the noise and the crowds, where everyone is hustling=
 for different reasons. Anecdotally, I=E2=80=99ve noticed that people who f=
led California during the lockdowns and resettled in Austin, Nashville, Mia=
mi, etc. never returned to the Golden State. In contrast, most of the peopl=
e who left NY during the lockdowns eventually returned. As a Millennial of =
a certain age who saw 9/11 and its aftermath, and who loved the Tobey Magui=
